{
  format: 1
  name: duration-exact-elapsed-order-not-text
  suite: scenario
  spec: ["#annex-b", "§B.1", "§A.1"]
  tags: ["ordering"]
  note: '''
    §B.1 duration: ascending order is "exact elapsed-duration order" — compare
    the elapsed time, not the ISO-8601 text (A.1: a duration's wire form is a
    canonical ISO-8601 duration string).

    Attack: a lexicographic sorter over the ISO-8601 strings. Elapsed values:
      PT9M  = 540 s
      PT10M = 600 s
      PT1H  = 3600 s
      PT90M = 5400 s
    Correct elapsed order:  PT9M < PT10M < PT1H < PT90M   ->  k9, k10, k1h, k90
    A text sorter compares "PT9M","PT10M","PT1H","PT90M" character by character
    after the shared "PT": position 3 splits '1' (PT10M, PT1H) below '9' (PT9M,
    PT90M); it yields PT10M < PT1H < PT90M < PT9M, i.e. k10, k1h, k90, k9 —
    WRONG, dropping the smallest elapsed value (PT9M, 9 minutes) to LAST.

    Every elapsed value is distinct, so `$sort: [d]` is already total; no
    identity tiebreaker is exercised here. Only `id` is projected, so no
    canonical duration spelling is asserted (Annex A does not pin whether e.g.
    PT90M canonicalizes to PT1H30M) — only row order, which the elapsed order
    fully determines.
  '''

  package: {
    $liasse: 1
    $app: "t.annexb.duration@1.0.0"
    $model: {
      rows: {
        $key: "id"
        id: "text"
        d: "duration"
      }
      $public: {
        by_d: { $view: ".rows { id, $sort: [d] }" }
      }
    }
    $data: {
      rows: {
        k90: { d: "PT90M" }
        k9: { d: "PT9M" }
        k1h: { d: "PT1H" }
        k10: { d: "PT10M" }
      }
    }
  }

  steps: [
    { watch: "public.by_d", id: "w1",
      expect_init: { value: [
        { id: "k9" }
        { id: "k10" }
        { id: "k1h" }
        { id: "k90" }
      ] } }
  ]
}
